<TITLE> Indonesia graft body says might name more suspects </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JAKARTA, Jan 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Indonesia's anti-corruption agency, which this week named three senior central bank officials as suspects in a probe into misuse of funds at a foundation linked to the bank, said on Wednesday it might name more suspects. The Corruption Eradication Commission, known by its Indonesian acronym KPK, did not give details of the investigation or what the suspects, who include Central Bank Governor Burhanuddin Abdullah, are accused of doing. But it said it might ban overseas travel for Bank Indonesia's governor and two other senior officials. "There is a possibility that there will be more suspects. Please give us the opportunity to investigate this using the three suspects as the gate," Antasari Azhar, head of KPK, told a press conference on Wednesday. Abdullah told a hastily called news conference on Tuesday that he was surprised and saddened to hear he had been named as a suspect by KPK. He did not give details. Over the past decade, various institutions in Indonesia have investigated the central bank, mainly focusing on its controversial role in a massive bail-out of the banking sector during the 1997-98 Asian financial crisis. KPK launched its investigation after the Supreme Audit Agency found evidence that a foundation linked to Bank Indonesia had made illegal payments to members of parliament and paid for legal assistance for top central bank officials. The legal assistance was related to separate investigations into billions of dollars of emergency funds extended by the central bank to troubled commercial banks at the height of the crisis a decade a
